{
  "doc_id": "11205",
  "text": "Mechanisms involved in ozone-induced lung damage have been investigated in animal models [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . In general, experimental animals require significantly higher doses of O 3 exposure than humans [CITATION_8] to reach comparable amounts of O 3 concentration in the distal lung. Measurement of various parameters in bronchoalveolar lavage (BAL) revealed that resting rodents exposed to high O 3 doses (2 ppm) were either comparable (polymorphonuclear leukocytes (PMNs), protein) or lower (macrophages) than the exercising human exposed to considerably lower O 3 exposures (0.44 ppm). Therefore, it is necessary that rodents be exposed to high O 3 concentrations to better enable extrapolation of findings from animal studies to human. Our laboratory has demonstrated ozone-dependent changes in mice in epithelial permeability, inflammatory mediators, and susceptibility to pneumonia [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . The changes in epithelial permeability have been attributed to TLR-4-mediated changes in iNOS activity [CITATION_12] . A role for oxidative stress in ozoneinduced pathophysiology has been postulated based on increases in F 2 -isoprostane [CITATION_13] , a lipid peroxidation product, as well as reductions in inflammatory mediators and allergen sensitivity by antioxidant treatment [CITATION_14] . The involvement of oxidative stress is further supported by studies in which genetic polymorphisms influence the response to ozone [CITATION_15] . Although the pathophysiology of ozone-induced lung damage is incompletely understood, these mechanistic and genetic association studies provide a strong rationale for oxidative stress [CITATION_16] playing a key role in the response to ozone exposure.",
